AGI - The new Stability and Growth Pact, approved today by the European Parliament, provides for countries with a debt of more than 90% of GDP which should reduce it by a percentage point each year; Countries with a debt between 60% and 90% will have to reduce it by 0.5%. Member States will also have to leave a tax bearing of 1.5% of GDP below the 3% mandatory threshold; to set up this reserve, the annual adjustment should be 0.4% of GDP (in case of four-year return plans), which could be reduced to 0.25% of GDP (in return plans for 7 years).
&nbsp;
The new provisions are less restrictive > of the current requirement that each country should reduce the debt each year of a twentieth (5%) of excess more than 60%. Governments will be allowed to deviate from the net expenditure path of 0.3% of GDP on an annual basis and 0.6% of GDP cumulatively during the monitoring period. Countries will be able to extend the adjustment period from four to seven years using the investments and reforms included in their Pnrr.
&nbsp;
For States which violate the rules on deficits and which must make an annual fiscal effort half a point of GDP, the increase in interest payments will be excluded from the calculation in the period 2025-27. Of course, 3% of GDP for deficit and 60% of GDP for debt remain. All countries will provide medium-term plans* by 30 September which will delegate their spending objectives and the ways in which investment and reform will be undertaken. Member States with high levels of deficit or debt will receive pre-plan indications on expenditure targets. Expenditure on defence > will be considered a 'relevant factor' in the calculation of return plans from the deficit. Moreover - at the request of the Pe - national expenditure for co-financing of EU-funded programmes will be excluded from the calculation of government expenditure.&nbsp;

